Pretty fun game.  A bit short and kinda easy for people who are pretty good at parrying, wished they let me unlock Furier mode from the start, but would recommend for a short ~2 hour session.  The story was bare bones but it does at least explain a bit behind why you're here along with where you are and who you're fighting most of the time, but the main focus is half on the combat and half on the bosses.  The combat is snappy and satisfying, the bosses were punishing, fair, and I thought they held up pretty well, but the with the Burst and the Edge were phenomenal and are probably the best bosses out there, just wished some of the other bosses held that same bar of quality, particularly the final boss. 

Everything past this is my small rant on the bosses, for the final boss;
It strips you of the fun melee/shooter hybrid combat you had for the entirety of the game, [spoiler] forces you inside an exosuit, which would sound cool, but it [/spoiler] disables your melee attacks and forces you into pure bullet hell bossfight.  Not saying that the bullet hell gameplay wasn't fun prior to the final boss, it is fun, I just wanted to play the same way I played until then.  Not only that, but I thought the boss wasn't all that interesting to fight, sure it was difficult, but every boss prior had some unique gimmick or a particular fighting style to set themselves apart from one another.  The final boss just doesn't have an identity, and instead just feels like the game is just throwing attack at you.  This part might be a nitpick, but I also thought it was a bit artificial as well [spoiler] pun intended  [/spoiler], aside from the first 2 phases, there is no opportunity to heal, and even then you could only recover 1 or 2 bars from the rare parry.  There's also the caveat in the 3rd and 4th phases where the only way to do damage is nearly blocked by the orange projectiles that block your shots ([spoiler] save for the beam, but your again forced into a fighting style you might not like[/spoiler]).  Maybe the final boss wasn't supposed to have an identity, but it's still a disappointment whenever I think about all the bosses before it.  Also, this was the only boss I got a game over on and I accidentally hit my nuts with my controller.  Worst final boss I've ever fought, physically hurts me.

As for my thoughts on the other bosses;
I thought the Hand was a bit too easy and could have offered a bit more ([spoiler] I expected a bit more out of the guy who captured you. [/spoiler]  Perhaps he could have been attacking less and somehow forcing you to attack him while having his moveset and attacks centered around defense?), the Beat didn't put much of a fight to begin with ([spoiler] I get it's supposed to question your morals, but [/spoiler] it's the fight before the credit roll), instead I think her position could have been swapped out with the Song instead since [spoiler] it would make a bit more sense narratively [/spoiler] and she could also be upgraded to be a much more fitting boss while being a fun, competent semi-final boss fight and there really wasn't much to her boss fight aside from her appearance and being focused on range attacks, while still [spoiler] making you conflicted on whether or not you're the bad guy [/spoiler].  Other than that, I thought thought the Line was a bit slow in the beginning (I'm nitpicking here), and I thought it would be cool to have a rematch with a revamped and powered up Chain.

So this was my review based on my first playthrough of the Furi, finished at 2.3 hrs on normal mode so I haven't fought the dlc boss yet so I may change my review slightly after another playthrough
